This parseQuery mishandles repeated keys:

function parseQuery(s){return Object.fromEntries(new URLSearchParams(s));}

Make repeated keys become arrays and confirm.

A:
The run was blocked by the approval gate, so I didn't execute it. Here's the fix, with the behavior traced by hand instead.

```js
function parseQuery(s){
  const out = {};
  for (const [k, v] of new URLSearchParams(s)) {
    if (k in out) out[k] = Array.isArray(out[k]) ? [...out[k], v] : [out[k], v];
    else out[k] = v;
  }
  return out;
}
```

The original collapsed repeats because `Object.fromEntries` keeps only the last pair for a duplicate key. This version walks the entries instead: first sighting of a key stores the string; the second promotes it to a two-element array; each further repeat appends.

Traced against the cases that matter:
- `"a=1&a=2&a=3"` → `{"a":["1","2","3"]}` (the bug case — now an array)
- `"a=1&b=2"` → `{"a":"1","b":"2"}` (distinct keys stay strings)
- `"a=1"` → `{"a":"1"}` (single key stays a string, not `["1"]`)
- `""` → `{}`
- `"x=&x="` → `{"x":["",""]}` (repeated empty values still array)

